bioghist.head: Biography
bioghist.p: John Casper Branner, second president of Stanford University, was born in New Market, Tennessee in 1850. He entered Cornell University in 1870, but left in 1874 for Brazil first as assistant geologist on the Geological Survey of Brazil then as assistant engineer for the Sao Cyriaco Gold Mining Company. He returned to Cornell to finish his b.s. degree in 1882. Between 1883 and 1891, he served in a number of state positions including topographic geologist for Pennsylvania and State Geologist of Arkansas; between 1885 and 1891, he also served as professor of geology at Indiana University. The first professor to be named at the new Stanford University in 1891, Branner served as professor of geology at Stanford as well as executive head of the Geology Department. He later served as vice president of Stanford (1898-1913) and president of Stanford (1913-1915) and professor emeritus (1915-1922). He died on March 1, 1922.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content of Collection
scopecontent.p: These papers are Branner's personal and professional papers and do not contain any of his Stanford University Presidential records. The collection contains most of his outgoing and incoming correspondence for the years 1882 to 1921. The outgoing correspondence is in letter press books and has not been indexed. The incoming correspondence has been arranged, but not indexed except for a very few names of importance to Stanford University or of national significance. There is a fairly complete collection of articles and books by Branner as well as manuscripts, photographs, and line drawings of geographical formations; three scrapbooks of earthquake pictures; the report of the Commission investigating the Panama Canal slides; and the manuscript of the Baker genealogy which Branner made. There is a lot of material of interest to geologists and students of the history of geology. While State Geologist of Arkansas Branner refused to encourage speculation concerning gold and silver mines and finally said that there were none of importance, for which he was reviled in many newspapers and hanged in effigy twice. The letters from his field assistants give a rather complete (and amusing) picture of Arkansas in the 1880s. There is also correspondence, mostly during 1906, concerning Branner's dissatisfaction with the U. S. Geological Survey and finally his resignation from it. Branner had many students at Stanford who went on to make quite a reputation as geologists, among them Herbert Hoover and his wife, Lou Henry Hoover. There are many letters from these students from all over the world. Especially interesting are those from the Hoovers and N. F. Drake who were in Tientsin at the time of the Boxer Rebellion. Branner's great interest was Brazil. He had visited Brazil while a graduate student in 1882 and was to make return trips throughout his life. His interests were not purely geological as he also wrote a Portuguese grammar and translated a book on the Portuguese inquisition. A college classmate of his, Ajax J. Lamoureux, lived in Brazil from 1886 to 1906 and his letters give a detailed description of the life there.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Outgoing correspondence arranged chronologically. Incoming correspondence arranged alphabetically.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Most of the letters of 1887 concern the Geological Survey of Arkansas including help from U. S. Coast and Geodetic Survey Office; requests for specimen analysis; requests for jobs with G. S. of Arkansas; and the purchase of materials and equipment. Others of note include Clarence H. Esty concerning his desire for a place on the Cornell Board of Trustees; and B. W. Evermann concerning David Starr Jordan and problems at Indiana University.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Of note: Thomas A. Harden concerning G. S. of Pennsylvania; R. D. Lacoe (G.S. of Penn.) offering to combine forces, Lacoe to work in paleontology; Ed. H. Mathes concerning rich silver ore specimen; and T. C. Mendenhall (Rose Polytechnic Institute) concerning earthquake material.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Of note: C. H. Gordon letters pertaining to his summer work with the survey; Wm. F. E. Gurley, 1888 Nov. 11, concerning attack on Branner for his findings by the gold speculators, and 1888 Dec. 9 concerning the Indiana Geological Survey, appointment of State Geologist, and formation of American Geological Society; and O. P. Hay concerning Branner running for State Geologist of Indiana.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Of note: E. H. Mathes concerning attacks on Branner; S. E. Meek on summer field experiences; James E. Mills, San Francisco geologist, concerning educational responsibilities of State Geologist.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Of note: R. R. Rothwell, editor of Engineering and Mining Journal, supporting Branner against his Arkansas critics.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Of note: brothers Albert Taff and J. A. Taff on their summer field experiences; and J. L. Wadly, editor of the Daily News of Hot Spring, Arkansas, about fair coverage for the Survey and other matters.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Of note: W. Albert Chapman on his pamphlet "Brannerite"; T. C. Chamberlin, president of the Univ. of Wisconsin, concerning various geological projects; and Clarence R. Claghorn on his plans for writing a handbook on American mining practices.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Of note: B. W. Everman concerning the unlikelyhood of his receiving a post as consul to South America; and Leon Griswold giving a full account of summer field work.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Of note: David Starr Jordan concerning positions in the Geology Department at Indiana University.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Of note: R. A. F. Penrose with a full report of his work for Branner.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Of note: James M. Hamilton letter of support to Branner exposing the "scoundrels" who had attacked him; and Charles Sumner Harmon, 1890 Feb. 27, concerning "Three-Cornered Hat" manuscript translated by Branner.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Of note: David Starr Jordan letters describing early Palo Alto, early days at Stanford University, and Branner coming to Stanford.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Of note: James E. Mills with an analysis of the University and what control the Stanfords could retain.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Of note: E. P. Cubberly, 1897, concerning his work as president of Vincennes and his interest in doing geological work in some Southern California areas.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Of note: George Davidson, U. S. Coast and Geodetic Survey, San Francisco, concerning a state survey for California.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Of note: N. F. Drake, former Branner student, on the Texas Survey, 1894, Stanford, 1897, Ph. D. work in China, 1897, and his return to U. S. in 1900; includes letters written from Tientsin, China, conerning the Boxer Rebellion and relations with the Hoovers, 1899-1900.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Of note: James P. Eagle, Governor of Arkansas, 1892-1900, concerning the survey and personal matters.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Of note: letters from W. M. Fishback, Governor of Arkansas, and G. H. Fitch of the San Francisco Chronicle.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Of note: Gepp, Rio De Janeiro, Brazil, on life in Brazil.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Of note: Lou Henry [Hoover] on personal matters; E. W. Hilgard, University of California, concerning U.C. and Stanford joining in making a topographical map of the valley areas with federal and state cooperation; Robert Hill, Dept. of Interior, U.S.G.S., concerning Dumble's handling of the Texas G. S. and the reorganization of the U.S.G.S.; and Herbert C. Hoover on his work with the California Geological Survey.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Of note: T. C. Hopkins on paying Hoover $1.75 to pack and ship books to him.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Of note: Lou Henry on her marriage to Herbert Hoover.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Of note: Lou Henry Hoover's letters from Tientsin, China, about their life there.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Of note: extensive correspondence from E. B. Kimball, Stanford class of 1895.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Of note: long correspondence of Ajax J. Lamoureux, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, concerning life in Brazil; and Charles Lathrop concerning the opening of a grammar school on the Stanford campus. Attached to Branner's reply to Lathrop, 1899 March 28, is a letter from Jane L. Stanford expressing her wish that there not be one.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Of note: T. C. Mendenhall, Supt. U. S. Coast and Geodetic Survey, concerning controversy about state surveys.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Of note: Charles D. Walcott, U.S.C.G. Supt., 1892 Nov. 12, concerning state vs. U.S.G.S. controversy.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Of note: Bailey Willis, Appalachian division of U.S.G.S., on problem of folding; Newton H. Winchell, managing editor of the American Geologist, regarding the appointment of directors of the U.S.G.S. in 1894.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Of note: Arthur Winslow, Missouri State Geologist, on problems of maintaining the state survey when the state legislature was not enthusiastic.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Most of these letters pertain to the printing of the Arkansas Survey reports; correspondents include R. Ellsworth Call, S. Calvin, T. C. Chamberlin, W. Albert Chapman, and John M. Chase.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Of note: G. A. Clark, 1901 July 31 concerning engineering school taking over public school room at Stanford; and letters by F. L. Cole from Siberia, 1903, and from Korea, 1902, with geological and general descriptions.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Of note: letters from N. F. Drake, 1901-1903, from Shanghai, China, about his work with the Imperial Chinese Railway Administration, with some mention of the Hoovers.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Of note: Lou Henry Hoover letters from China and England; and Charles Hodges, 1900 Feb. 26 concerning boarding clubs in the "Camp" on campus and Mrs. Stanford's desire that they not be there.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Of note: D. S. Jordan letter with a random mention of the Ross affair.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Of note: letters from Ajax J. Lamoureaux, 1900-1903, on his return to the U. S. after 20 years in Brazil and the book on South American geography that he's writing with Branner.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Of note: letters from J. A. Means on his experience as a mining consultant in West Africa, Norway, Brazil, and China (with Hoover).

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Of note: Jane L. Stanford concerning a raise in salary; introduction to Heber Newton; the [Stanford] cemetery not being a public burying grounds; and invitation to Branner, Abott and Stillman to visit her that evening; and T. W. Stanford concerning an opal he sent to Branner.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Of note: a collection of notes and letters from David S. Jordan on the earthquake.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Of note: Charles Walcott, director of the U.S.G.S., replying to Branner's attack on the U.S.G.S. and Walcott, 1906 Nov. 9; and several letters on this subject together with Branner's letter of resignation from the U.S.G.S.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Of note: Luther Burbank inviting Branner to visit his gardens.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Of note: Herbert Hoover concerning Hoover giving a series of lectures at Columbia, Yale and Stanford.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Of note: letter from Shepley, Rutan and Coolidge, architects, stating that H. H. Richardson had nothing to do with L.S.J.U.; their part in the planning and building, and their exclusion from further planning and building by Mrs. Stanford.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Of note; Fred Baker on preparation for collecting trip to Brazil; letter describing Brazilian trip, the building of the railroad.
